-An inspection program, which requires daily, weekly, monthly and annual inspections of process equipment, alarm systems, and management practices, with a procedure for documenting and correcting any deficiencies identified in inspections;
-A standard operating procedure for the transfer of flammable and combustible liquids;
-A standard operating procedure for ensuring that incompatible materials are not consolidated together;
-A waste analysis plan which ensures that the waste received by the Facility conforms to the waste as initially represented by each generator, and that each waste stream is managed correctly;
-A security plan to prevent unknowing or unwanted access to the facility; and
-A training plan which ensures that employees at the facility are adequately trained to perform their job duties knowledgeably and safely.
In addition, the Facility has instituted a Program Level 2 prevention program consisting of the following elements:
-Process Safety Information including Material Safety Data Sheet (MSDS) for regulated substances;
-Process Hazard Analysis, including a systematic evaluation of potential hazards associated with handling regulated substances and development of recommendations for improving safety;
-Operating procedures regarding transfer, storage and processing of regulated substances;
-Training of workers on operating procedures;
-Maintenance procedures to ensure mechanical integrity of equipment;
-Compliance audits of the prevention program to be conducted every three years; and
-Incident investigation to document releases and accidents of regulated substances.
5.0 Five-year Accident History
During the past five (5) years (April 2006 to March 2011), there has not been any accident involving any RMP regulated substance that qualifies for reporting under 40 CFR Part 68.  
